    title: "Sliding Window Maximum",
    desc: `1. PROBLEM OVERVIEW
-------------------
The Sliding Window Maximum problem requires finding the maximum element in each window of size k as the window slides through an array. This is a classic problem in algorithmic optimization.

2. REAL-WORLD SCENARIO
----------------------
Used in financial analysis for moving averages, network traffic monitoring for peak detection, and real-time data processing systems where you need to track maximum values in rolling time windows.

3. DETAILED OBJECTIVE
---------------------
Given an array nums, there is a sliding window of size k which is moving from the very left of the array to the very right. You can only see the k numbers in the window. Each time the sliding window moves right by one position, return the max sliding window.

4. PROBLEM STATEMENT
--------------------
Implement an efficient algorithm using a deque to maintain the maximum elements in O(N) time.

5. FUNCTION SIGNATURE
---------------------
vector<int> maxSlidingWindow(vector<int>& nums, int k)

6. INPUT FORMAT
---------------
First line: space-separated integers (nums array)
Second line: single integer k (window size)

7. OUTPUT FORMAT
----------------
Space-separated integers representing maximums for each window position.

8. CONSTRAINTS
--------------
* 1 ≤ nums.length ≤ 10^5
* 1 ≤ k ≤ nums.length
* -10^4 ≤ nums[i] ≤ 10^4

9. EDGE CASE REQUIREMENTS
-------------------------
* k = 1: return the array itself
* k = nums.length: return single maximum
* Array with all negative numbers
* Array with duplicates

10. TIME COMPLEXITY EXPECTATIONS
--------------------------------
* O(N) time complexity required
* O(N) space for result, O(K) for deque

11. MEMORY CONSTRAINTS
----------------------
* Deque should store at most K elements
* Result array of size N-K+1

12. SAMPLE INPUT
----------------
1 3 -1 -3 5 3 6 7
3

13. SAMPLE OUTPUT
-----------------
3 3 5 5 6 7

14. DETAILED EXPLANATION
------------------------
Windows of size 3:
[1,3,-1] → max = 3
[3,-1,-3] → max = 3
[-1,-3,5] → max = 5
[-3,5,3] → max = 5
[5,3,6] → max = 6
[3,6,7] → max = 7

15. ADDITIONAL NOTES
--------------------
* Use deque to store indices in decreasing order
* Remove elements smaller than current from back
* Remove elements outside current window from front

16. PERFORMANCE REQUIREMENTS
----------------------------
* Must handle 10^5 elements efficiently
* Linear time solution mandatory`,
