    title: "Median of Two Sorted Arrays",
    desc: `1. PROBLEM OVERVIEW
-------------------
Finding the median of two sorted arrays is a fundamental problem in algorithm design that requires logarithmic time complexity. This problem appears in database query optimization and statistical analysis.

2. REAL-WORLD SCENARIO
----------------------
In distributed databases, you often need to find medians across multiple sorted partitions. This algorithm enables efficient median finding without merging all data, crucial for real-time analytics on partitioned datasets.

3. DETAILED OBJECTIVE
---------------------
Given two sorted arrays nums1 and nums2 of size m and n respectively, return the median of the two sorted arrays.

4. PROBLEM STATEMENT
--------------------
The overall run time complexity should be O(log (m+n)).

5. FUNCTION SIGNATURE
---------------------
double findMedianSortedArrays(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2)

6. INPUT FORMAT
---------------
Two lines of space-separated integers representing the two arrays.

7. OUTPUT FORMAT
----------------
A decimal number representing the median (with appropriate precision).

8. CONSTRAINTS
--------------
* nums1.length == m
* nums2.length == n
* 0 <= m <= 1000
* 0 <= n <= 1000
* 1 <= m + n <= 2000
* -10^6 <= nums1[i], nums2[i] <= 10^6

9. EDGE CASE REQUIREMENTS
-------------------------
* One array is empty
* Arrays of different sizes
* Odd and even total elements
* Negative numbers and zeros

10. TIME COMPLEXITY EXPECTATIONS
--------------------------------
* O(log(min(m,n))) time complexity
* Binary search on smaller array

11. MEMORY CONSTRAINTS
----------------------
* O(1) auxiliary space
* No additional data structures

12. SAMPLE INPUT
----------------
1 3
2

13. SAMPLE OUTPUT
-----------------
2.0

14. DETAILED EXPLANATION
------------------------
Merged array: [1,2,3], median is 2.0 (middle element for odd count).

15. ADDITIONAL NOTES
--------------------
* Use binary search to partition arrays
* Ensure correct partition for median calculation
* Handle both odd and even cases

16. PERFORMANCE REQUIREMENTS
----------------------------
* Must achieve O(log(min(m,n))) time
* Handle large arrays efficiently`,
